<p>  Composition of the delegation .........................................................................................................  28 </p>


<p><b>  Introduction 
</b></p>
<p>1. The Working Group on the Universal Periodic Review, established in accordance 
</p>
<p>with Human Rights Council resolution 5/1 of 18 June 2007, held its twenty-first session 
</p>
<p>from 19 to 30 January 2015. The review of Sweden was held at the 11th meeting, on 
</p>
<p>26 January 2015. The delegation of Sweden was headed by Annika S&#246;der, State Secretary, 
</p>
<p>Ministry for Foreign Affairs. At its 17th meeting, held on 29 January 2015, the Working 
</p>
<p>Group adopted the report on Sweden. 
</p>
<p>2. On 13 January 2015, the Human Rights Council selected the following group of 
</p>
<p>rapporteurs (troika) to facilitate the review of Sweden: Argentina, Latvia and the Republic 
</p>
<p>of Korea. 
</p>
<p>3. In accordance with paragraph 15 of the annex to resolution 5/1 and paragraph 5 of 
</p>
<p>the annex to resolution 16/21, the following documents were issued for the review of 
</p>
<p>Sweden: 
</p>
<p>(a) A national report submitted/written presentation made in accordance with 
</p>
<p>paragraph 15 (a) (A/HRC/WG.6/21/SWE/1);  
</p>
<p>(b) A compilation prepared by the Office of the United Nations High 
</p>
<p>Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR) in accordance with paragraph 15 (b) 
</p>
<p>(A/HRC/WG.6/21/SWE/2); 
</p>
<p>(c) A summary prepared by OHCHR in accordance with paragraph 15 (c) 
</p>
<p>(A/HRC/WG.6/21/SWE/3).  
</p>
<p>4. A list of questions prepared in advance by Azerbaijan, Belgium, the Czech Republic, 
</p>
<p>Ecuador, Israel, the Netherlands, Norway, Slovenia, Spain and the United Kingdom of 
</p>
<p>Great Britain and Northern Ireland was transmitted to Sweden through the troika. Those 
</p>
<p>questions are available on the extranet of the universal periodic review (UPR). 
</p>
<p><b> I. Summary of the proceedings of the review process 
</b></p>
<p><b> A. Presentation by the State under review 
</b></p>
<p>5. The delegation of Sweden said that promoting and respecting human rights for all 
</p>
<p>was a core value and a central priority of the Government. Sweden appreciated that civil 
</p>
<p>society, including organizations representing indigenous peoples and national minorities, 
</p>
<p>had contributed to the preparations for the current UPR session.  
</p>
<p>6. In a statement of government policy, made in October 2014, the Prime Minister had 
</p>
<p>emphasized that racism and prejudices in society restricted people&#8217;s lives. Furthermore, he 
</p>
<p>had emphasized that there must be no place in Sweden for anti-Semitism, antiziganism, 
</p>
<p>Islamophobia or Afrophobia. The delegation explained that the fight against racism and 
</p>
<p>xenophobia involved awareness-raising, government contributions to non-governmental 
</p>
<p>organizations, and continuing dialogue with groups subjected to racism and xenophobia. 
</p>
<p>The Swedish police was currently carrying out an assignment to bolster its efforts to 
</p>
<p>combat hate crime.  
</p>
<p>7. The delegation stated that it was essential to ensure the free exchange of opinions. 
</p>
<p>Although freedom of expression and freedom of the press were enshrined in the 
</p>
<p>Constitution of Sweden, constitutional laws also clearly regulated the content of 
</p>
<p>publications in such a case as the criminal offence of agitation against a national or ethnic 
</p>
<p>group. </p>


<p>8. The delegation stated that combating intolerance, hatred and violent extremism was 
</p>
<p>a global problem that needed to be dealt with collectively. The Government had recently 
</p>
<p>appointed a national coordinator against violent extremism.  
</p>
<p>9. The delegation stated that Sweden had a feminist government and that gender 
</p>
<p>equality was to permeate all government policies. The main tool in reaching that goal was 
</p>
<p>gender mainstreaming, as well as enhanced gender budgeting and work to combat violence 
</p>
<p>against women. 
</p>
<p>10. In 2014, Sweden had ratified the Council of Europe Convention on Preventing and 
</p>
<p>Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence (Istanbul Convention) and 
</p>
<p>introduced new legislation that strengthened the protection against forced marriage and 
</p>
<p>child marriage. 
</p>
<p>11. While the total pay gap between women and men had decreased by 3 percentage 
</p>
<p>points between 1994 and 2013, there was still a pay gap in Sweden of around 13 per cent. 
</p>
<p>The Government had appointed the Delegation for Gender Equality in Working Life to 
</p>
<p>investigate the different conditions for women and men and to propose actions to promote 
</p>
<p>gender equality and reduce the pay gap.  
</p>
<p>12. The delegation confirmed that the fight against all forms of discrimination, including 
</p>
<p>multiple discrimination, remained a key objective of the Government.  
</p>
<p>13. The Discrimination Act of 2009 had been amended on 1 January 2015 to include 
</p>
<p>inadequate accessibility for people with disabilities as a new form of discrimination.  
</p>
<p>14. A comprehensive strategy had been adopted in 2013 with the purpose of improving 
</p>
<p>and strengthening the situation for lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) persons 
</p>
<p>in Sweden. A committee of inquiry was currently looking into the question of whether 
</p>
<p>transgender persons should be protected by the criminal law provisions on hate crimes and 
</p>
<p>hate speech, which already covered the ground of sexual orientation.  
</p>
<p>15. Strengthening the protection of national minority languages was an element in 
</p>
<p>protecting the rights of Sweden&#8217;s national minorities.  
</p>
<p>16. The delegation stated that the work aimed at eliminating discrimination against 
</p>
<p>Roma and antiziganism was a priority for the Government. The national strategy for Roma 
</p>
<p>inclusion, which had been adopted in 2012, placed special emphasis on the principle of 
</p>
<p>non-discrimination and on Roma participation and input for its implementation. A special 
</p>
<p>commission against antiziganism had been appointed.  
</p>
<p>17. The delegation reported that, in 2013, the media had exposed a police register of 
</p>
<p>over 4,000 people. According to the media, the main purpose for setting up the register had 
</p>
<p>been to map individuals on the basis of their Roma background. The investigation carried 
</p>
<p>out by the Commission on Security and Integrity Protection had concluded that the 
</p>
<p>processing of personal data by the police was against the law in several aspects. The Police 
</p>
<p>Authority had been commissioned to report to the Government in February 2015 on the 
</p>
<p>measures that had been taken to ensure that the legal framework was applied accurately and 
</p>
<p>that the required guidelines and administrative practices were in place to prevent any 
</p>
<p>discrimination. With regard to the affected individuals&#8217; entitlement to compensation, about 
</p>
<p>3,000 applications for compensation had already been approved. 
</p>
<p>18. The delegation noted that since 2011, the Swedish Constitution had explicitly 
</p>
<p>recognized the Sami as a people. In 2011, Finland, Norway and Sweden had initiated 
</p>
<p>negotiations on a Nordic Sami convention.  
</p>
<p>19. In 2010, the right of the Sami Parliament to participate in municipal planning and to 
</p>
<p>monitor consideration of Sami needs, including reindeer husbandry interests in land and 
</p>
<p>water use, had been extended. Furthermore, the Minerals Act and Minerals Ordinance had </p>


<p>been amended in 2014 so as to increase Sami involvement in the process of issuing permits 
</p>
<p>for exploration for minerals.  
</p>
<p>20. With regard to the mental health challenges facing reindeer herders, notably their 
</p>
<p>increased risk of suicide, the Government had acknowledged that there was a need for more 
</p>
<p>efforts in order to reduce such risks; a number of proposals were being looked into.  
</p>
<p>21. Sweden was constantly seeking ways to strengthen the rights of the child, including 
</p>
<p>the rights of children to express their views on issues concerning them. Since October 2014, 
</p>
<p>preparatory work on the incorporation of the Convention on the Rights of the Child into 
</p>
<p>Swedish legislation had been prioritized by the Government. 
</p>
<p>22. The delegation explained that in 2014, approximately 7,000 unaccompanied minors 
</p>
<p>had applied for asylum in Sweden and that the best interests of the child were always to be 
</p>
<p>taken into account. The Swedish Migration Board had worked actively to trace the minors&#8217; 
</p>
<p>parents or other guardians.  
</p>
<p>23. More than 6,000 persons under the age of 18, with residence in Sweden, were 
</p>
<p>stateless. The delegation noted that the recognition of the State of Palestine would give 
</p>
<p>most of those children citizenship. Amendments to the Swedish Citizenship Act, with the 
</p>
<p>aim of reducing statelessness, would enter into force on 1 April 2015.  
</p>
<p>24. The delegation stated that, in Sweden, pretrial detention and restrictions should only 
</p>
<p>be used when necessary and proportionate. The reasons for the detention were regularly 
</p>
<p>reviewed. It was important that the length of the pretrial detention be kept as short as 
</p>
<p>possible and that only necessary restrictions be used. The Prosecution Authority and the 
</p>
<p>Prison and Probation Service were both taking steps to reduce the isolation of detainees.  
</p>
<p>25. The Government was also examining ways of improving the overall situation for 
</p>
<p>young offenders, including finding ways to ease any solitary confinement of young 
</p>
<p>detainees.  
</p>
<p>26. The delegation reported that Sweden combined strong protection of the rights of the 
</p>
<p>individual with efforts to prevent any interference with the right to privacy. The Foreign 
</p>
<p>Intelligence Act and the Signals Intelligence Act contained mechanisms for legal security 
</p>
<p>and control to ensure that the requirement of integrity protection was met.  
</p>
<p>27. The delegation stated that signals intelligence at the National Defence Radio 
</p>
<p>Establishment was conducted within the detailed framework of Swedish legislation, under 
</p>
<p>strict judicial control and with parliamentary oversight. The Government reported to 
</p>
<p>Parliament annually, through a written communication, on the signals surveillance 
</p>
<p>conducted under the Act. The system was aimed at ensuring that signals intelligence was 
</p>
<p>carried out in accordance with the national legislation protecting privacy as well as with the 
</p>
<p>country&#8217;s obligations under international human rights law.  
</p>
<p>28. On the issue of investigations into alleged police misconduct, the delegation referred 
</p>
<p>to the establishment on 1 January 2015, at the national level, of the independent and 
</p>
<p>separate Department of Special Investigations, within the Swedish police.  
</p>
<p>29. The delegation reported that the Government, in its budget bill for 2015, had 
</p>
<p>announced that it intended to deliver to Parliament a systematic strategy for human rights 
</p>
<p>work in Sweden, one important aspect of which was to set out how independent monitoring 
</p>
<p>of the implementation of human rights in the country could be organized. 
</p>
<p><b> B. Interactive dialogue and responses by the State under review 
</b></p>
<p>30. During the interactive dialogue, 89 delegations made statements. Recommendations 
</p>
<p>made during the dialogue are to be found in section II of the present report. </p>


<p>31. Montenegro welcomed the drawing up of the national action plan for human rights, 
</p>
<p>the long-term strategy for Roma inclusion, and Sweden&#8217;s mid-term report. It enquired about 
</p>
<p>activities undertaken to address racially motivated hate speech against visible minorities. 
</p>
<p>32. Morocco welcomed the adoption of measures to promote gender equality and to 
</p>
<p>combat violence against women, and of policy to improve the situation of persons with 
</p>
<p>disabilities. It highlighted the efforts to combat discrimination, racism and xenophobia, and 
</p>
<p>the initiatives against discrimination and offensive treatment in schools. 
</p>
<p>33. Namibia noted the anti-discrimination efforts, including the budget allocation, which 
</p>
<p>had enjoyed an increase from 2013, as well as the protection against discrimination 
</p>
<p>associated with age that had applied to sectors of society covered by the Discrimination Act 
</p>
<p>starting from 1 January 2013. 
</p>
<p>34. Belgium welcomed the progress made on children&#8217;s rights. It enquired whether the 
</p>
<p>process of incorporating the Convention on the Rights of the Child into Swedish legislation 
</p>
<p>had begun and whether the Government could commit to a deadline to complete that 
</p>
<p>incorporation. 
</p>
<p>35. Nicaragua welcomed the legislative and institutional advances since the first UPR of 
</p>
<p>Sweden, and highlighted the adoption of the law on combating discrimination and 
</p>
<p>particularly multiple discrimination. 
</p>
<p>36. Norway welcomed Sweden&#8217;s announcement about incorporating the Convention on 
</p>
<p>the Rights of the Child into Swedish law. It noted concerns over the slow progress in 
</p>
<p>addressing Sami land rights and the restrictive terms of reference of the Boundary 
</p>
<p>Commission, and made reference to the importance of ratifying International Labour 
</p>
<p>Organization (ILO) Convention No. 169. 
</p>
<p>37. Pakistan made recommendations. 
</p>
<p>38. Costa Rica highlighted the adoption of the new Act on Criminal Responsibility for 
</p>
<p>Genocide, Crimes against Humanity and War Crimes, and shared the concern of the 
</p>
<p>Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination at the reported increase of racially 
</p>
<p>motivated hate speech against minorities.  
</p>
<p>39. Poland acknowledged the efforts made to implement the recommendations of the 
</p>
<p>first UPR cycle and noted that adoption of the law on crimes against humanity in 2014 was 
</p>
<p>an important step in the fight against torture.  
</p>
<p>40. Portugal commended Sweden&#8217;s efforts to combat all kinds of discrimination, 
</p>
<p>especially against minorities, and to promote equality. In that regard, Portugal noted the 
</p>
<p>establishment by Sweden of the office of the Equality Ombudsman. 
</p>
<p>41. Qatar welcomed the 2010 strategy for strengthening child rights, the new action plan 
</p>
<p>for the protection of children against human trafficking, exploitation and sexual assault, and 
</p>
<p>education programmes that incorporated the rights of the child. 
</p>
<p>42. Romania commended Sweden for its mid-term report, and noted positively 
</p>
<p>Sweden&#8217;s approval of the Istanbul Convention, its adoption of the strategy for Roma 
</p>
<p>inclusion for 2012&#8211;2032, and the setting-up of the commission against anti-gypsyism.  
</p>
<p>43. The Russian Federation was concerned at the unlawful use of force by the police and 
</p>
<p>xenophobic rhetoric against national and religious minorities. It also noted the growth in 
</p>
<p>crimes of hatred, racism and xenophobia. 
</p>
<p>44. Rwanda commended the measures to combat discrimination and to boost knowledge 
</p>
<p>about xenophobia among minors, and the efforts to promote gender equality and salary 
</p>
<p>parity. It noted its appreciation for the conviction of Stanislas Mbanenande for the crime of 
</p>
<p>genocide in Rwanda.  </p>


<p>45. Senegal welcomed the steps taken by Sweden to withdraw reservations to 
</p>
<p>international human rights instruments, and the adoption of legislative measures to protect 
</p>
<p>unaccompanied children and to combat trafficking in persons and the sexual exploitation of 
</p>
<p>children.  
</p>
<p>46. Serbia commended Sweden on instituting the office of the Equality Ombudsman. 
</p>
<p>Serbia encouraged continued efforts to promote the integration of migrants and to 
</p>
<p>strengthen cooperation with civil society, with a view to reinforcing migrants&#8217; influence in 
</p>
<p>society.  
</p>
<p>47. Sierra Leone commended Sweden for its human rights record and support to 
</p>
<p>developing countries through official development assistance. Sierra Leone urged Sweden 
</p>
<p>to further promote religious tolerance and social integration among the country&#8217;s various 
</p>
<p>ethnic groups and immigrant communities.  
</p>
<p>48. Slovakia commended Sweden for prioritizing its human rights policy, and 
</p>
<p>acknowledged its gender equality activities and its initiatives to combat anti-gypsyism. It 
</p>
<p>encouraged Sweden to implement the recommendations of the Committee against Torture 
</p>
<p>on legal safeguards for persons deprived of their liberty. 
</p>
<p>49. Slovenia welcomed Sweden&#8217;s assistance through development cooperation. It noted 
</p>
<p>the challenges of hate crime, intolerant political discourse and a persistent gender pay gap, 
</p>
<p>as well as some concerns about the right to privacy, in connection with the mass 
</p>
<p>interception of communications. 
</p>
<p>50. Spain welcomed the measures adopted on children&#8217;s rights, in response to 
</p>
<p>recommendations made by Spain in 2010. It also welcomed the efforts that had been made 
</p>
<p>to better protect the rights of persons with disabilities. 
</p>
<p>51. Sri Lanka appreciated the implementation of the 2014 action plan for the protection 
</p>
<p>of children from trafficking and sexual exploitation, the priority accorded to gender 
</p>
<p>equality, and the efforts that had been made to strengthen protections against 
</p>
<p>discrimination. 
</p>
<p>52. The State of Palestine welcomed the efforts made to combat discrimination and 
</p>
<p>xenophobia and to address the gender wage gap, as well as the appointment of special hate 
</p>
<p>crimes investigators. 
</p>
<p>53. The Sudan commended Sweden&#8217;s ratification of most United Nations core 
</p>
<p>conventions on human rights and the adoption of two national plans of action for human 
</p>
<p>rights. 
</p>
<p>54. Thailand commended the progress made in incorporating international human rights 
</p>
<p>obligations into national legislation. It welcomed the establishment of the office of the 
</p>
<p>Equality Ombudsman, and noted that hate crime and online racism continued to proliferate. 
</p>
<p>55. The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia noted that the Swedish foreign 
</p>
<p>ministry had held regular and frequent meetings on human rights issues with civil society 
</p>
<p>organizations. It commended the country&#8217;s contribution to international development. 
</p>
<p>56. Timor-Leste recognized the commitment of Sweden to making human rights 
</p>
<p>protection a priority. It appreciated the strategy for Roma inclusion for 2012&#8211;2032, the 
</p>
<p>special hate crime investigator, and the strengthened measures to combat trafficking. 
</p>
<p>57. Togo noted that despite progress in the fight against discrimination, difficulties 
</p>
<p>remained regarding racism. Persons with a migrant background and Swedes of African 
</p>
<p>descent were often targeted; new measures were therefore required to better protect persons 
</p>
<p>targeted by discrimination, racism and xenophobia. </p>


<p>58. Tunisia welcomed the pioneering role of Sweden in promoting and protecting 
</p>
<p>human rights and freedom of expression on the internet. Tunisia noted the measures taken 
</p>
<p>to implement UPR recommendations, particularly the adoption of human rights action 
</p>
<p>plans, and welcomed Sweden&#8217;s asylum policies. 
</p>
<p>59. Turkey praised Sweden&#8217;s achievements in human rights, especially in the prevention 
</p>
<p>of violence against women, and its ratification of the Istanbul Convention. It was concerned 
</p>
<p>about racially motivated and/or religiously intolerant hate speech and an increase in 
</p>
<p>associated crimes.  
</p>
<p>60. Ukraine commended the strength of human rights protections in Sweden and cited 
</p>
<p>domestic implementation via national action plans. It lauded the open consultations with 
</p>
<p>civil society organizations, as well as the cooperation with international mechanisms and 
</p>
<p>institutions. 
</p>
<p>61. The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland recognized Sweden&#8217;s 
</p>
<p>prioritization of human rights. It acknowledged protections against discrimination, but 
</p>
<p>recognized outstanding challenges impacting on vulnerable groups, including the Roma, 
</p>
<p>and urged enhanced protections for stateless persons.  
</p>
<p>62. The United States of America lauded Sweden&#8217;s commitment to human rights and its 
</p>
<p>leadership in promoting internet freedoms. However it noted reports of discrimination 
</p>
<p>against certain ethnic and religious minorities, and was concerned by insufficient training 
</p>
<p>for judges investigating human trafficking.  
</p>
<p>63. Uzbekistan commended the national action plans, the establishment of the office of 
</p>
<p>the Equality Ombudsman, and the Roma inclusion strategy. However, it noted concerns 
</p>
<p>expressed by treaty bodies about hate speech on racial and religious grounds, coercive 
</p>
<p>treatment of persons with mental disabilities, and industrial activities in traditional Sami 
</p>
<p>territory. 
</p>
<p>64. Albania welcomed constitutional protections against discrimination, including on 
</p>
<p>the grounds of sexual orientation, and the ratification of the Istanbul Convention. It noted 
</p>
<p>with satisfaction the budget allocations for the sustainable protection of human rights, 
</p>
<p>particularly for organizations working in the disability sector.  
</p>
<p>65. Algeria appreciated Sweden&#8217;s participatory approach with civil society in the 
</p>
<p>drafting of the national report. It commended the adoption of two action plans and 
</p>
<p>encouraged the adoption of a third. It encouraged the creation of a new national human 
</p>
<p>rights institution in compliance with the Paris Principles. 
</p>
<p>66. Angola welcomed the measures taken to raise children&#8217;s and adolescents&#8217; awareness 
</p>
<p>about xenophobia and similar forms of intolerance. It noted Sweden&#8217;s efforts to comply 
</p>
<p>with its international commitments to protect the rights of vulnerable persons, particularly 
</p>
<p>migrants. 
</p>
<p>67. Argentina commended Sweden for its new 2014 and 2015 action plan for the 
</p>
<p>protection of children against human trafficking, sexual exploitation and sexual assault, and 
</p>
<p>for the legislative efforts made to combat discrimination.  
</p>
<p>68. Armenia lauded the ongoing measures for gender equality, alongside provisions for 
</p>
<p>children and persons with disabilities. It commended the protection of the rights of national 
</p>
<p>minorities, as well as the free exercise of the cultural and religious rights of persons of 
</p>
<p>Armenian origin living in Sweden.  
</p>
<p>69. Australia praised the consistent respect for human rights and civil liberties, 
</p>
<p>specifically the promotion of gender equality and elimination of violence against women. It 
</p>
<p>commended the inquiry commissioned in 2014 to consider a specific provision on 
</p>
<p>criminalizing torture in Swedish law.  </p>


<p>70. Austria commended Sweden&#8217;s commitment to the global advancement of human 
</p>
<p>rights. Austria remained concerned at reports of discrimination against the Sami, 
</p>
<p>particularly in relation to land rights, water and resources. It referred to concern on the part 
</p>
<p>of the Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination at increased reports of 
</p>
<p>racially motivated hate speech and hate crimes. 
</p>
<p>71. Azerbaijan noted concerns expressed by some treaty bodies about discrimination, 
</p>
<p>xenophobia and racist attitudes against Muslims, Afro-Swedes, Roma and Jews, attacks 
</p>
<p>against the places of worship of religious minorities, and the increasingly high rate of 
</p>
<p>suicide among persons with disabilities. 
</p>
<p>72. Replying to comments made and questions raised, Sweden stated that it had 
</p>
<p>extensive legislation in place that could be used to punish various expressions of racism, 
</p>
<p>xenophobia, religious intolerance, homophobia and transphobia. The assignment given to 
</p>
<p>the Swedish police was aimed at improving the rate of resolved hate crime cases; that report 
</p>
<p>would be followed up on. 
</p>
<p>73. The delegation stated that most penal provisions relevant to combating hate speech 
</p>
<p>and hate crime also applied to crimes committed online. 
</p>
<p>74. In response to the recent attacks against Swedish mosques, the Swedish police had 
</p>
<p>prioritized investigations to find those responsible and bring them to justice. Dialogue 
</p>
<p>between the police and religious organizations needed to intensify. The Government had 
</p>
<p>invited representatives from the Muslim community to a round-table talk on Islamophobia 
</p>
<p>being held in Europe in early 2015. 
</p>
<p>75. The Government had invited representatives from the Jewish community to discuss 
</p>
<p>issues of anti-Semitism, and additional funds had been allocated for enhanced security 
</p>
<p>measures to protect the Jewish community in Sweden. 
</p>
<p>76. Concerning antiziganism, a white paper on abuses and violations against Roma 
</p>
<p>during the twentieth century had been presented in 2014, and a commission against anti-
</p>
<p>ziganism had been set up. 
</p>
<p>77. As the largest number of reported hate crimes was in relation to Afrophobia, the 
</p>
<p>Government intended to give the Equality Ombudsman an assignment to carry out 
</p>
<p>awareness-raising measures during 2015 and 2016. 
</p>
<p>78. Independent studies had concluded that Sweden fulfilled the requirements set out in 
</p>
<p>ILO Convention No. 169 in most respects, and that the main stumbling blocks were rights 
</p>
<p>of ownership and possession over lands, and reindeer grazing rights. The delegation 
</p>
<p>reported that the issue of land rights was also addressed in the draft Nordic Sami 
</p>
<p>Convention, and that the Government hoped that this process could be a catalyst to finding 
</p>
<p>a solution to outstanding issues. 
</p>
<p>79. Regarding the issue of a national human rights institution, Sweden had assessed that 
</p>
<p>national action plans for human rights were an appropriate method of work. The two 
</p>
<p>committees of enquiry regarding systematic work on human rights in Sweden and their 
</p>
<p>recommendations, as well as the follow-up to the UPR, would constitute the basis for 
</p>
<p>Sweden&#8217;s deliberations on how to deliver a system in which independent monitoring of the 
</p>
<p>implementation of human rights could take place. The delegation reported that the Swedish 
</p>
<p>Association of Local Authorities and Regions had made an agreement with the Government 
</p>
<p>about strengthening human rights at work at the local level, and the Government had 
</p>
<p>adopted a decision about supporting Sweden&#8217;s country boards to work with human rights. 
</p>
<p>80. In Sweden, the age of criminal responsibility was 15 years. A person under the age 
</p>
<p>of 18 could only be placed in detention if there were extraordinary reasons for that </p>


<p>detention. Sweden would report to the Committee against Torture on the legal safeguards 
</p>
<p>for minors in detention, by November 2015. 
</p>
<p>81. Sweden had established a government committee to look at the possibility of having 
</p>
<p>a special criminal provision on torture, and would present a report in September 2015. 
</p>
<p>82. Sweden had signed the International Convention for the Protection of All Persons 
</p>
<p>from Enforced Disappearance, in 2007. The question of its ratification was on its agenda, 
</p>
<p>but work on ratification had not yet started. 
</p>
<p>83. The delegation confirmed that there was no general obligation under international 
</p>
<p>law to recognize diplomatic asylum. 
</p>
<p>84. Bahrain noted the measures taken to combat trafficking in persons and uphold the 
</p>
<p>rights of victims, and welcomed the initiatives taken to raise awareness among students 
</p>
<p>about the danger of xenophobia. It asked about the plan to improve access to education by 
</p>
<p>migrant families. 
</p>
<p>85. Bangladesh commended Sweden on exceeding the United Nations target for official 
</p>
<p>development assistance. It noted the concern expressed by the Committee on the 
</p>
<p>Elimination of Racial Discrimination about racist and extremist organizations and about an 
</p>
<p>increase of racially motivated hate speech against religious minorities, Afro-Swedes and 
</p>
<p>Roma. 
</p>
<p>86. The Netherlands appreciated the efforts of Sweden to combat terrorism, noting the 
</p>
<p>concern that the use of surveillance technology could violate the right to privacy. It 
</p>
<p>acknowledged efforts to deal with discrimination against the Sami and Roma minorities, 
</p>
<p>stating that this required continued vigilance. 
</p>
<p>87. Benin commended the efforts and progress in the field of economic, social and 
</p>
<p>cultural rights, and the promotion of the right to development, including the support for the 
</p>
<p>realization of the Millennium Development Goals. 
</p>
<p>88. Bosnia and Herzegovina commended Sweden on being an exemplary democratic 
</p>
<p>country. It asked about obstacles to ratifying the International Convention on the Protection 
</p>
<p>of the Rights of All Migrant Workers and Members of Their Families, the International 
</p>
<p>Convention for the Protection of All Persons from Enforced Disappearance, and the 
</p>
<p>Optional Protocol to the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights. It 
</p>
<p>shared the concerns of the Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women 
</p>
<p>that immigrant, refugee and minority women continued to suffer multiple forms of 
</p>
<p>discrimination. 
</p>
<p>89. Botswana commended the amendment to the Penal Code to strengthen protection 
</p>
<p>against harassment and protection against forced and child marriage, and an action plan to 
</p>
<p>protect children against trafficking. However it noted the concerns expressed by treaty 
</p>
<p>bodies about ethnic discrimination and hate crimes. 
</p>
<p>90. Brazil commended the legislative amendment that recognized the Sami as an 
</p>
<p>indigenous people. It shared the concern expressed by the Committee on the Elimination of 
</p>
<p>Racial Discrimination about hate crimes, noting that the reorganization of the police should 
</p>
<p>be seized as an opportunity to prevent ethnic profiling and build trust with local 
</p>
<p>communities. 
</p>
<p>91. Bulgaria commended the adoption of two national human rights action plans. It 
</p>
<p>appreciated measures taken to combat discrimination and xenophobia, such as the 
</p>
<p>appointment of a special investigator and the establishment of the office of the Equality 
</p>
<p>Ombudsman, and efforts to combat anti-Semitism and Islamophobia. </p>


<p>92. Canada noted Sweden&#8217;s agreement in 2010 to improve dialogue and consultation 
</p>
<p>with the Sami people on government policy affecting them and in the development of 
</p>
<p>legislation. Canada asked for information on progress achieved, including with respect to 
</p>
<p>Sweden&#8217;s Arctic policy.  
</p>
<p>93. Chad noted with satisfaction Sweden&#8217;s presentation of a mid-term report on the 
</p>
<p>implementation of UPR recommendations, and its regular consultation with civil society 
</p>
<p>organizations on questions pertaining to human rights and equal rights for certain 
</p>
<p>population groups. 
</p>
<p>94. Chile celebrated the efforts to implement human rights policies nationally and 
</p>
<p>internationally. It shared the concern at discriminatory attitudes detailed in the national 
</p>
<p>report and encouraged Sweden to continue adopting further measures in that regard. 
</p>
<p>95. China cited concern over efforts to enhance anti-discrimination education and 
</p>
<p>protect minority rights, specifically in combatting xenophobia, gender-based discrimination 
</p>
<p>and intolerance on the internet. It also referred to hate crimes, and to measures to combat 
</p>
<p>trafficking, exploitation and sexual attacks against children. 
</p>
<p>96. Comoros took note of the commitments and actions undertaken for the respect of all 
</p>
<p>human rights. Comoros welcomed the actions taken by Sweden in support of development 
</p>
<p>and highlighted its exemplary openness and hospitality to migrants.  
</p>
<p>97. C&#244;te d&#8217;Ivoire noted the reforms undertaken at the national level, particularly the 
</p>
<p>legislative provisions on gender equality and the access to public services for persons with 
</p>
<p>disabilities, members of minorities, migrants and asylum seekers. It welcomed Sweden&#8217;s 
</p>
<p>involvement in humanitarian activities. 
</p>
<p>98. Croatia welcomed the progress achieved in implementing recommendations 
</p>
<p>accepted by Sweden during its first UPR and encouraged the Government to continue 
</p>
<p>working actively to ensure full and equal enjoyment of all human rights for all, without 
</p>
<p>distinction.  
</p>
<p>99. Cuba recognized progress achieved in different areas and noted remaining 
</p>
<p>challenges, as mentioned in the national report, including discrimination. It expressed 
</p>
<p>concern at discriminatory statements made by far-right politicians, the existence of racist 
</p>
<p>organizations, and increased incitement to hatred, especially on the internet. 
</p>
<p>100. The Czech Republic appreciated the informative presentation by the Swedish 
</p>
<p>delegation on human rights challenges and achievements. 
</p>
<p>101. Denmark commended Sweden&#8217;s commitment to human rights and underlined the 
</p>
<p>importance of monitoring the human rights situation. It welcomed the work undertaken by 
</p>
<p>Sweden to progress in the negotiations on the draft Nordic Sami Convention. 
</p>
<p>102. Ecuador recognized the efforts to comply with recommendations received in 2010, 
</p>
<p>particularly the measures taken to guarantee the rights of persons with disabilities, and 
</p>
<p>highlighted progress in combating discrimination, xenophobia and human trafficking. 
</p>
<p>103. Egypt welcomed positive developments related to women&#8217;s rights, the rights of the 
</p>
<p>child and combating human trafficking. Egypt noted that discrimination and societal 
</p>
<p>hostility against Roma, Muslims and migrants; hate crimes, including the torching of 
</p>
<p>mosques; and alleged racial profiling deserved specific attention. 
</p>
<p>104. Estonia highlighted Sweden&#8217;s policies on women&#8217;s rights and on minority and 
</p>
<p>indigenous peoples, its leadership on the internet freedom resolutions and its role as a 
</p>
<p>humanitarian aid donor. It welcomed the strategy for Roma inclusion and the work with the 
</p>
<p>draft Nordic Sami convention. </p>


<p>105. Finland was pleased to note the open consultations with civil society, the 
</p>
<p>Ombudsman&#8217;s highlighting of multiple discrimination, and the report on discrimination 
</p>
<p>against the Roma in Sweden. Finland emphasized the possible usage of Me&#228;nkieli and 
</p>
<p>Finnish minority languages.  
</p>
<p>106. France welcomed Sweden&#8217;s commitment to human rights, particularly within the 
</p>
<p>Human Rights Council.  
</p>
<p>107. Gabon commended the three-year initiative running from 2012 to 2014 in the field 
</p>
<p>of education and training, which included measures to give children and adolescents a 
</p>
<p>better understanding of xenophobia, as well as the efforts to improve the care of 
</p>
<p>unaccompanied minors in municipalities.  
</p>
<p>108. Germany commended an exemplary record of human rights protections, but 
</p>
<p>observed that xenophobic and Islamophobic parties had gained ground, resulting in anti-
</p>
<p>Muslim sentiments being voiced in the media and subsequent increases in hate speech and 
</p>
<p>hate crimes.  
</p>
<p>109. Greece acknowledged the efforts made to tackle discrimination based on religion, 
</p>
<p>but stated that more needed to be done given increased racism-oriented activities in the 
</p>
<p>country. Greece commended the appointment of a national coordinator for combating 
</p>
<p>violence in intimate relations and suggested that the recommendations in her report be 
</p>
<p>implemented.  
</p>
<p>110. Guatemala welcomed the confirmation in 2011 of the recognition of the Sami as a 
</p>
<p>people and the Nordic cooperation projects aimed at strengthening the rights of Sami to 
</p>
<p>maintain and develop their language, culture, way of life and community life. 
</p>
<p>111. Honduras congratulated Sweden on its efforts to combat discrimination through the 
</p>
<p>adoption of normative, institutional and policy measures, particularly the consultation with 
</p>
<p>civil society organizations working to promote the equality of children, persons with 
</p>
<p>disabilities, LGBT persons and national minorities.  
</p>
<p>112. Hungary welcomed the progress in strengthening the rights of the child, but was 
</p>
<p>concerned at the reported increase in hate crimes. Hungary asked about the results of pilot 
</p>
<p>projects for Roma inclusion, and of the main findings and conclusions on establishing a 
</p>
<p>national institution compliant with the Paris Principles.  
</p>
<p>113. Iceland noted that Sweden was a global standard-bearer for the promotion and 
</p>
<p>protection of human rights. Iceland encouraged accelerated efforts to address persistent 
</p>
<p>problems of xenophobic and Islamophobic discourse, and applauded the intended 
</p>
<p>incorporation of the Convention on the Rights of the Child into Swedish law. 
</p>
<p>114. India commended the recent initiative to sensitize young people against xenophobia 
</p>
<p>and other forms of intolerance. India encouraged Sweden to address the discrepancies in 
</p>
<p>access to employment, housing, health care and education between native Swedes and 
</p>
<p>foreign-born persons.  
</p>
<p>115. Indonesia welcomed the efforts to combat violence against women and to protect 
</p>
<p>children&#8217;s rights and ensure respect for the rights of migrants. Indonesia also appreciated 
</p>
<p>the co-hosting in January 2015 of a high-level event entitled Staying Together: Dialogue in 
</p>
<p>the Face of Violent Extremism. 
</p>
<p>116. The Islamic Republic of Iran expressed serious concerns over racist and xenophobic 
</p>
<p>crimes against Roma and Sinti, and crimes against minorities, including the targeting of 
</p>
<p>Muslims with harassment, verbal threats, sabotage and vandalism. </p>


<p>117. Ireland commended Sweden&#8217;s strong commitment to human rights, the rule of law 
</p>
<p>and freedom of the media. It noted that functions of the Ombudsman for Children did not 
</p>
<p>include the power to accept individual complaints.  
</p>
<p>118. Israel congratulated Sweden on its leading work on promoting the human rights of 
</p>
<p>the sexual orientation and gender identity community. It echoed concerns by the Office of 
</p>
<p>the Ombudsman for Children, particularly on the human rights of children deprived of their 
</p>
<p>liberty in remand prisons and police cells. 
</p>
<p>119. Italy noted concerns on the lack of a broader mandate for the Equality Ombudsman. 
</p>
<p>It welcomed the measures taken to safeguard children from sexual exploitation, and noted 
</p>
<p>the concerns about the low level of public awareness of child sex tourism. 
</p>
<p>120. Kuwait noted the challenges in fighting discrimination and welcomed the 
</p>
<p>establishment of the office of the Equality Ombudsman to fight against all forms of 
</p>
<p>discrimination against vulnerable groups, particularly foreigners and refugees. 
</p>
<p>121. Lebanon welcomed the efforts of Sweden to adopt international standards and 
</p>
<p>develop national legislation. It commended the numerous initiatives to combat 
</p>
<p>discrimination and xenophobia as a reflection of the commitment to strengthening human 
</p>
<p>rights and democratic values.  
</p>
<p>122. Libya noted that despite considerable progress made in various areas, some 
</p>
<p>challenges in the area of human rights still remained, particularly in fighting discrimination. 
</p>
<p>123. Lithuania encouraged Sweden to exchange its experience with other countries that 
</p>
<p>were seeking to make progress in the area of human rights protection. It recognized the 
</p>
<p>steps taken to ensure the protection of children by including a new crime in the Penal Code 
</p>
<p>in 2009. 
</p>
<p>124. Malaysia acknowledged progress made, including in promoting and protecting the 
</p>
<p>rights of persons with disabilities. Malaysia noted the Government&#8217;s dialogue with religious 
</p>
<p>associations to combat xenophobia and religious intolerance. In addition, it noted that 
</p>
<p>Sweden still faced the challenges of racism, intolerance, Islamophobia and xenophobic 
</p>
<p>attitudes towards non-citizens and other minorities. 
</p>
<p>125. Trinidad and Tobago welcomed the adoption of the plan against human trafficking. 
</p>
<p>Trinidad and Tobago believed that further work was needed to combat discrimination 
</p>
<p>against minorities and to enhance the rights of disabled persons. 
</p>
<p>126. Uruguay welcomed the elaboration of a third human rights plan. The establishment 
</p>
<p>of a national human rights institution would support human rights achievements. Uruguay 
</p>
<p>stated that the humanitarian situation and rights of any person sought by the Government 
</p>
<p>should be considered and protected. 
</p>
<p>127. The Republic of Moldova asked about the findings of the interim report of the 
</p>
<p>committee of inquiry into compulsory residential care for children and adolescents and 
</p>
<p>recommended the introduction of a new form of care home for unaccompanied children. It 
</p>
<p>noted the successful implementation of the second human rights action plan. 
</p>
<p>128. South Africa commended the successful implementation of some UPR 
</p>
<p>recommendations and encouraged Sweden to continue to make every effort for the 
</p>
<p>promotion, protection and fulfilment of all human rights, including the right to 
</p>
<p>development. 
</p>
<p>129. The Philippines recognized the important contribution by Sweden on migration and 
</p>
<p>development and lauded Sweden for amending its anti-discrimination laws to make it easier 
</p>
<p>for victims to seek redress. The Philippines was interested in knowing about initiatives to 
</p>
<p>safeguard the rights of the Sami and Roma. </p>


<p>130. Mexico welcomed the recognition of the Sami as an indigenous population, and the 
</p>
<p>efforts to promote awareness about xenophobia and other forms of intolerance among 
</p>
<p>children and adolescents. It encouraged Sweden to continue combating racist, xenophobic, 
</p>
<p>Islamophobic and anti-Semitic propaganda.  
</p>
<p>131. Ghana commended the commitment by Sweden to the UPR process. Ghana referred 
</p>
<p>to the legacy of Raoul Wallenberg regarding the protection of minorities, while noting 
</p>
<p>human rights concerns that had been expressed by the Committee on the Elimination of 
</p>
<p>Racial Discrimination and the Committee against Torture. 
</p>
<p>132. The Swedish delegation stated that, while racist organizations could exist in Sweden, 
</p>
<p>racist actions were criminalized.  
</p>
<p>133. The implementation of the strategy for Roma inclusion was characterized by Roma 
</p>
<p>influence and participation.  
</p>
<p>134. Sweden had allocated a considerable amount of money, including for shelters, in 
</p>
<p>order to implement all measures to end men&#8217;s violence against women, violence and 
</p>
<p>oppression in the name of honour, violence in same-sex relationships, female genital 
</p>
<p>mutilation, child marriages and forced marriages. 
</p>
<p>135. The delegation stated that, in 2012, the Government had appointed a national 
</p>
<p>coordinator against violence in close relationships. Sweden expected the final report in May 
</p>
<p>2015 of the committee of enquiry charged with developing a national strategy to achieve 
</p>
<p>the aim of ending men&#8217;s violence against women.  
</p>
<p>136. If business did not live up to the commitment of applying quotas for women in 
</p>
<p>business, the Government might consider legislating on that matter.  
</p>
<p>137. The delegation referred to Sweden&#8217;s proactive role in abolishing corporal 
</p>
<p>punishment against children both in Sweden and internationally. Sweden planned to create 
</p>
<p>a national knowledge centre on violence against children to coordinate and compile 
</p>
<p>knowledge and to support actors in their work against corporal punishment.  
</p>
<p>138. The issue of child poverty had been highly prioritized by the Government, and some 
</p>
<p>county administrative boards had supported local authorities in producing action plans, 
</p>
<p>suited to local conditions, to deal with child poverty. 
</p>
<p>139. Sweden was the country in Europe receiving the highest number of asylum-seeking 
</p>
<p>unaccompanied children. In 2014, 87 per cent of unaccompanied minors had been granted 
</p>
<p>residence permits. Sweden, per capita, had received more refugees than any other European 
</p>
<p>Union country. 
</p>
<p>140. The principle of non-refoulement had long been a part of Swedish asylum law. 
</p>
<p>Refusal of entry or expulsion may never be enforced if the person would be in danger of 
</p>
<p>suffering the death penalty or torture. 
</p>
<p>141. The delegation confirmed that it was not possible to accede to the International 
</p>
<p>Convention on the Protection of the Rights of All Migrant Workers and Members of Their 
</p>
<p>families. 
</p>
<p>142. Regarding questions about human trafficking, the delegation stated that Sweden had 
</p>
<p>presented, in 2014, an action plan for the protection of children against human trafficking, 
</p>
<p>exploitation and sexual assaults. 
</p>
<p>143. The delegation reported that the Swedish Foreign Intelligence Inspectorate was 
</p>
<p>tasked with verifying that the defence intelligence authorities followed the Foreign 
</p>
<p>Intelligence Act. The Foreign Intelligence Court was a special court hearing applications 
</p>
<p>for permits to conduct signals intelligence. All signal intelligence that a national defence </p>


<p>radio establishment might conduct required a permit from the Foreign Intelligence Court, 
</p>
<p>whose aim it was to limit intrusions in individual privacy.  
</p>
<p>144. In closing, the Swedish delegation thanked all the delegations that had asked 
</p>
<p>questions and made recommendations. The UPR was an important opportunity to reflect on 
</p>
<p>the human rights situation in Sweden. Sweden was proud of the progress made and also 
</p>
<p>saw the UPR process as an opportunity to improve. Sweden would carefully consider the 
</p>
<p>recommendations made. It would continue to engage with civil society and reflect on the 
</p>
<p>UPR process, and consider how recommendations could best be addressed and 
</p>
<p>implemented. Sweden would undertake interministerial consultations to follow up on the 
</p>
<p>dialogue and the recommendations. <b> 
</b></p>
<p><b> II. Conclusions and/or recommendations</b>&#61482;&#61482;<b> 
</b></p>
<p>145. <b>The recommendations formulated during the interactive dialogue and listed 
</b></p>
<p><b>below have been examined by Sweden and enjoy the support of Sweden:</b> 
</p>
<p>145.1. <b>Consider ratification of the third protocol to the Convention on the 
</b></p>
<p><b>Rights of the Child, thereby establishing a procedure for the presentation of 
</b></p>
<p><b>communications (Belgium); 
</b></p>
<p>145.2. <b>Consider ratification of the ILO convention on indigenous peoples 
</b></p>
<p><b>(Uzbekistan); consider ratifying ILO Convention No. 169 (Guatemala); 
</b></p>
<p><b>consider ratifying ILO Convention No. 169 (Nicaragua); 
</b></p>
<p>145.3. <b>Consider ratifying ILO Convention No. 169 (Brazil); 
</b></p>
<p>145.4. <b>Consider ratifying other international human rights conventions, 
</b></p>
<p><b>including ILO Convention No. 189 (Philippines); consider ratification of ILO 
</b></p>
<p><b>convention on decent work for domestic workers (Uzbekistan); 
</b></p>
<p>145.5. <b>Initiate the process to incorporate the Convention on the Rights of 
</b></p>
<p><b>the Child into national legislation and continue the formulation of a third plan 
</b></p>
<p><b>of action for human rights (Albania); 
</b></p>
<p>145.6. <b>Adopt measures to incorporate the Convention on the Rights of the 
</b></p>
<p><b>Child into national legislation (Angola); 
</b></p>
<p>145.7. <b>Take measures to ensure the full incorporation of the provisions of 
</b></p>
<p><b>the Convention on the Rights of the Child in Swedish legislation (France); 
</b></p>
<p>145.8. <b>Take measures to incorporate the provisions of the Convention on the 
</b></p>
<p><b>Rights of the Child into Swedish law (Qatar); 
</b></p>
<p>145.9. <b>Work effectively on incorporating the the Convention on the Rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>of the Child into Swedish laws (Iceland); 
</b></p>
<p>145.10. <b>Consider establishing an independent national human rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>institution in accordance with the Paris Principles (Namibia); 
</b></p>
<p>145.11. <b>Consider establishing a national human rights institution in full 
</b></p>
<p><b>compliance with the Paris Principles (Ukraine); 
</b></p>
<p>145.12. <b>Consider creating a national human rights institution in compliance 
</b></p>
<p><b>with the Paris Principles (France); 
</b></p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> &#61482;&#61482; The conclusions and recommendations have not been edited. </p>


<p>145.13. <b>Consider establishing a national human rights institution in 
</b></p>
<p><b>accordance with the Paris Principles, as previously recommended (Indonesia); 
</b></p>
<p>145.14. <b>Consider establishing a national human rights institution, in 
</b></p>
<p><b>conformity with the Paris Principles, with a broad mandate, as soon as possible 
</b></p>
<p><b>(Ireland); 
</b></p>
<p><b>145.15. Consider heeding the call of the Committee on the Elimination of 
</b></p>
<p><b>Racial Discrimination for the establishment of a national human rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>institution in accordance with the Paris Principles (South Africa); 
</b></p>
<p>145.16. <b>Continue consultations initiated for the creation of a national human 
</b></p>
<p><b>rights institution in accordance with the Paris Principles (Togo); 
</b></p>
<p>145.17. <b>Consider developing Human Rights Indicators as an instrument that 
</b></p>
<p><b>allows for a more precise and coherent evaluation of national human rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>policies (Portugal); 
</b></p>
<p>145.18. <b>Consider developing a third action plan on human rights and 
</b></p>
<p><b>continue sharing its experience with regard to systematic human rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>implementation (Republic of Moldova); 
</b></p>
<p>145.19. <b>Continue its efforts to raise public awareness and to include human 
</b></p>
<p><b>rights education in the school curricula (Sudan); 
</b></p>
<p>145.20. <b>Give due attention to the issue of human rights education in the 
</b></p>
<p><b>current work on the third action plan on human rights by, inter alia, compiling 
</b></p>
<p><b>a report on the situation regarding human rights education in Sweden 
</b></p>
<p><b>(Finland); 
</b></p>
<p>145.21. <b>Continue to consult, and expand its dialogue with, civil society 
</b></p>
<p><b>organizations working in the area of human rights protection, particularly in 
</b></p>
<p><b>combating racial discrimination (Timor-Leste); 
</b></p>
<p>145.22. <b>Consider establishing an interministerial committee responsible for 
</b></p>
<p><b>the implementation of its international human rights obligations (Portugal); 
</b></p>
<p>145.23. <b>Continue to play an active role in international forums to fight racism 
</b></p>
<p><b>and paedophilia (Lebanon); 
</b></p>
<p>145.24. <b>Consider the introduction of a complaint mechanism for children at 
</b></p>
<p><b>the domestic level, as well as signature and ratification of the third Optional 
</b></p>
<p><b>Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of the Child on a communications 
</b></p>
<p><b>procedure (Ireland); 
</b></p>
<p>145.25. <b>Look into the possibility of prioritizing the rights of the child directly, 
</b></p>
<p><b>as a stand-alone issue, not just as a horizontal consideration in its human rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>policies (Hungary); 
</b></p>
<p>145.26. <b>Take appropriate measures to implement the recommendations of 
</b></p>
<p><b>the Committee on the Rights of the Child, including through education and 
</b></p>
<p><b>awareness-raising campaigns (Italy); 
</b></p>
<p>145.27. <b>Enhance efforts </b>&#8212;<b> </b>including within the &#8220;Strategy to Strengthen the 
</p>
<p>Rights of the Child in Sweden&#8221; &#8212;<b> to prevent and eliminate discrimination 
</b></p>
<p><b>against children belonging to ethnic minorities, child members of immigrant 
</b></p>
<p><b>families and child refugees and asylum seekers (Croatia); 
</b></p>
<p>145.28. <b>Explore ways and means of strengthening the ongoing efforts to 
</b></p>
<p><b>combat all forms of discrimination to improve the scope of protection against 
</b></p>
<p><b>discrimination at all levels in society (Sri Lanka); </b></p>


<p>145.29. <b>Fight against discrimination in society more effectively (Angola); 
</b></p>
<p>145.30. <b>Strengthen measures to combat all forms of discrimination (Gabon); 
</b></p>
<p>145.31. <b>Consolidate laws and regulations to fight all forms of discrimination, 
</b></p>
<p><b>racism and xenophobia (Lebanon); 
</b></p>
<p>145.32. <b>Be proactive in its measures to prevent discrimination against 
</b></p>
<p><b>immigrant, refugee and minority women who continue to suffer from multiple 
</b></p>
<p><b>forms of discrimination, and to combat violence against them (Bosnia and 
</b></p>
<p><b>Herzegovina); 
</b></p>
<p>145.33. <b>Consider the establishment of quotas to ensure a gender-balanced 
</b></p>
<p><b>representation in business administrative councils (France); 
</b></p>
<p>145.34. <b>Take concrete action to reduce the gender gap in decision-making 
</b></p>
<p><b>positions and ensure equal remuneration for men and women for work of equal 
</b></p>
<p><b>value (Sri Lanka); 
</b></p>
<p>145.35. <b>Continue to take measures to narrow the gender wage gap and 
</b></p>
<p><b>enhance the equal opportunities of work between men and women (State of 
</b></p>
<p><b>Palestine); 
</b></p>
